<DOC><DOCNO> AP890216-0149 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-16-89 1722EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Ramos-Plane     02-16 0246</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Ramos-Plane,0253</SECOND><HEAD>Philippines Defense Chief Has Trouble Getting Off the Ground</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos, whoseplane burned on the tarmac of a remote island in December, wasdelayed leaving a U.S.-run naval base Thursday when three of hisaircraft had engine trouble.   Ramos and his party boarded a Fokker aircraft at Subic Bay navalbase for a flight to another installation when the pilot discovereda faulty starter engine and circuit breaker, the Philippines NewsAgency said.   Ramos and the others waited about 90 minutes until a Philippinenavy BO-5 helicopter was flown to the base, 50 miles west of Manila.   The helicopter arrived at Subic and Ramos boarded. When the pilotrevved up the engines, however, the helicopter also developed enginetrouble and the takeoff was scrubbed.   Officials then telephoned Villamor Air Base in Pasay City todispatch a third aircraft _ a Fokker _ to retrieve Ramos, the newsagency said.   Minutes later, that Fokker also developed engine trouble and hadto return to Villamor. Finally, a UH-1 helicopter was sent to Subicand managed to take off with Ramos aboard, the agency said.   On Dec. 19, a Fokker carrying Ramos and 17 others caught firemoments after landing at Catarman on Samar island. All passengersescaped without injury but the plane was totally destroyed.   One of several helicopters sent to Catarman to fetch Ramos' partydeveloped engine trouble and ditched in the sea. No one was killed.</TEXT></DOC>